f citylife. It=92s one of those rare cities which has very modern parts, an=
d has yet preserved it=92s colonial and pre-colonial charm. Spend an evenin=
g wandering around its Old Quarter.\n\nSome
 of the best things to do yourself include:\nTrain Street: You might have s=
een it on Instagram. It=92s where you can go on a coffee date with your spo=
use, and have Vietnamese coffee while a train passes just inches from your =
knees. It makes for a heart racing
 experience and great photos.\n\nTrain timings:\nOn weekdays, aim for the 3=
:20-3:30 PM train passing through. Arrive by 2:45 PM to find a caf=E9 spot,=
 enjoy a drink, and watch the train pass safely (about 1-1.5 hours total).\=
nOn weekends: Arrive by 2:45 PM to
 find a caf=E9 spot, enjoy a drink, and watch the train pass safely (about =
1-1.5 hours total).\nOn both days, confirm train timing with your hotel or =
caf=E9 on the day as schedules can vary.\n\nHoan Kiem Lake: Located in the =
heart of Hanoi, walk by and enjoy the
 sunset at this serene lake. There is a temple connected by a bridge, that =
makes for memorable photos.\n\nShopping: Vietnam makes clothes and shoes fo=
r most major brands, hence you can find a great bargain everywhere! Find lu=
lulemons for just &#8377;500, and Nikes
 under &#8377;2500. Vietnam has a famous crafts tradition, and Old Quarter =
is the hub for it. You will find 36 streets with different specialities, su=
ch as bamboo or silk. Stroll down to Hang Gai Street, a 1000-year-old hub f=
or silk products. Here, you will find
 shops making custom outfits for you in 24-48 hours based on your selected =
fabric! Other notable streets are Hang Duaong St. (for dried fruits and loc=
al snacks) and Tich St. (for wood carvings).\n\nTa Hien Beer Street: End yo=
ur evening at this iconic street
 where you can have the famous cold Hanoi beer (one of the world=92s best d=
raught beers, which was a favourite of even Obama=92s) outdoor amidst Frenc=
h buildings with neon lights.\n\nWalking radius: ~1-1.5 kilometres and most=
 of our hotels are located in the Old
 Quarter itself.</div>
